"start":529,"end":534,"value":"f58ed5e3-a380-4e53-aa74-f7a8e7e7b3eb","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"474712b6-9c55-4a17-b64e-a13f67191ed2","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":537,"end":538,"value":"f219551f-c528-4666-8ada-4b95b7476b58","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"27833f37-90d8-4555-ae20-9314cdc76ff6","type":"style/italics","start":635,"end":640,"value":null,"zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"5790196b-9bed-41b9-be69-01cb1cb867b0","type":"language","start":635,"end":640,"value":"it","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"b4ed6654-e743-4a79-b3b7-212108d69ecb","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":635,"end":640,"value":"d009a377-5238-43de-838c-bee789dc57d9","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"5d8703b8-26e9-4b11-ae8b-d6a15a2aa339","type":"language","start":804,"end":822,"value":"la","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"6bd89c68-9037-4633-9cc9-a8f6e37a4d63","type":"style/italics","start":804,"end":822,"value":null,"zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"e946a3c8-fa08-42a9-8494-75c3235d5ed6","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":820,"end":822,"value":"a3fed3ec-1814-4027-a2d5-ac598b2fcb6f","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"bd379063-e11d-4315-a8f0-67ae7501464f","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":927,"end":928,"value":"f219551f-c528-4666-8ada-4b95b7476b58","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]}],"blockProperties":[]},{"id":"f54705ce-f3e9-4cb1-bd22-7e91995ce4b6","type":"standoff-editor-block","text":"At 2 o\u0027clock that Friday night (10 p.m.) the news came, and it was true that the Cardinal de\u0027 Medici had been elected Pope, with the name of Lione X. If there had been bonfires and rejoicings before, they were redoubled now, and in a different spirit; innumerable bundles of brushwood, great branches, baskets, barrels, and whatever each poor man chanced to have in his house; all the smallest streets of the city did their part, without stint and the people not yet being content, ran all over Florence to pull down the wooden roofs above the shops and everywhere, burning up everything. They put the whole city in great danger, and if the \u0022Eight\u0022 had not made a proclamation that no more roofs were to be pulled down and that the Piagnoni were no longer to be insulted, on pain of the gallows, even the tiled roofs would have been destroyed and the shops looted. And this nuisance lasted all Friday and Saturday, bonfires continuing, and illuminations on the Palagio, up on the cupola, on the gates, and everywhere, with so much firing of cannon and continual cries of Palle! Papa Lione! that it seemed as if the city were upside-down, and anyone who had seen it from overhead would have said: \u0022Florence is burning down the whole city,\u0022 for there was such a tumult of shouting, and fires, and smoke, and reports of the cannon, large and small; and on Sunday the same, and on Monday worse than ever. They placed up on the gallery behind the parapets of the Palagio, a gilt malmsey cask at each corner, full of firewood and other stuff to burn, and also on the ringhiera and in the Piazza many gilt casks\u00A0were burnt, accompanied by the continual sound of the spingards (small guns). It was really incredible what a number of fires there were in the city; every single person had one at his door. And in addition to this, they made several triumphal cars, and every evening set light to one in front of the house of the Medici in their honour; one was of discord, war, and fear, whilst another was of peace, and this latter they did not burn, as if to express that there was an end of all passions, and peace remained triumphant.","standoffProperties":[{"id":"e9a256fc-25cf-43bf-82fd-869acdbd3c7a","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":81,"end":99,"value":"bb12aae3-2a50-4ce4-a7d2-a892ae264f74","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"7393003f-2714-4a66-8075-0664a813c123","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":118,"end":121,"value":"c53cd0cd-02a5-4382-9987-ac2e2ccc88f8","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]